at all. But I -- I don't
know. I can't move on until I

02:44.033 --> 02:45.966 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
get that down.

02:45.966 --> 02:49.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: When you
overhear something or you record
something in your diary, is

02:49.400 --> 02:53.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
there kind of, aha, this
is something I can use?

02:53.233 --> 02:57.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID SEDARIS: I flew here
from London. I was at Newark
Airport waiting for someone

02:57.000 --> 02:59.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to pick me up.

02:59.066 --> 03:03.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I saw a couple, and they
were in their mid-60s. And
then she said to him, where's

03:03.400 --> 03:08.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the other suitcase? And he
said, what other suitcase? She
said, you left home dragging

03:10.400 --> 03:14.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
two suitcases behind you. Now
you have got one. The other one
is mine. Where's my suitcase?

03:15.066 --> 03:17.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You lost my suitcase.

03:17.100 --> 03:21.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I thought, wow. I mean, I have
been in a similar situation,
right? And just the entire look

03:24.333 --> 03:29.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on her face, like, if I could
leave you now, or if I could
kill you now, I would do it.

03:31.333 --> 03:35.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so I had to write about
that. Maybe one day, I would
write a story about arguing in

03:40.133 --> 03:45.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
public, and those would
come in handy in some way.

03:47.166 --> 03:51.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's also, like, if I were
going to remember yesterday,
I flew here in an airplane and

03:54.966 --> 03:59.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I did this and that. But that
was really the moment yesterday
where I felt like I was living

04:02.800 --> 04:07.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
my life, like I was in the
moment. I wasn't thinking about
the past or about the future.

04:09.800 --> 04:13.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was just right there living,
visiting and listening, watching
those people have an argument.

04:16.800 --> 04:20.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And that sense
is important to you somehow?

04:20.033 --> 04:25.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID SEDARIS: Well, because I
spend so much time like living
in the past or the future.

04:27.033 --> 04:31.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, I think most people
do, really. And the moments
when you're really present in

04:32.933 --> 04:36.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
your life can be
pretty rare, really.

04:36.066 --> 04:41.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Sedaris'
stories appear regularly
in "The New Yorker." On
the day we got together,

04:42.500 --> 04:44.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
